{{Orphan|date=July 2012}} {{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}} {{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Linda Stafford | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = Crying Wind | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{Birth date and age|Year|Month|Day}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Writer | language = | nationality = American | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = American Indians | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | portaldisp = Literature }}
'''Linda Davison Stafford''', also known as '''Crying Wind''', '''April Knight''', and '''Gwendlelynn Lovequist'''<ref name=Dictionary>Kievit, Joyce Ann. "Crying Wind" in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9eaSAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA79 Native American Women: A Biographical Dictionary]'', p. 79 (Bataille and Lisa, eds., [[Routledge]], 2001).</ref> is the author of several novels including ''Crying Wind'' and ''My Searching Heart'' which describe the experiences of a young [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] girl named "Crying Wind", and tell a story of [[Christian conversion]].<ref name=Today>"'Crying Wind' is Back, but Not as a Biography This Time". ''[[Christianity Today]]'', v. 25, p. 44 (January 23, 1981).</ref> Under the pseudonym Gwendlelynn Lovequist, she has written many love stories and romances, for publications such as ''[[Writer's Digest]]''.<ref name=Dictionary />
==Education and businesses== Stafford attended the [[University of Colorado]] (1961), the [[University of Texas]] (1966), the [[University of New Mexico]] (1967), and the [[University of Alaska]] (1969).<ref name=Dictionary /> She has run art galleries in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]], [[Anchorage]], and [[Oklahoma City]].<ref name=Dictionary />
== Publication and exposure == Stafford was described as a [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoo]] author and a [[Religious conversion|convert]] to [[Christianity]] when her book ''Crying Wind'' was published in 1977.<ref name=NC>Veach, Tucker. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CRwaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=syQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2495,5824919&dq=crying-wind&hl=en "A Remarkable Life"] ''[[Times-News (Hendersonville, North Carolina)|The Times-News]]'', p. 1 (April 20, 1978).</ref> Soon, she was touring, promoting her book and giving her conversion [[Testimony#Religion|testimony]] in churches and at conferences across the United States, dressed in Indian garb.<ref name=NC />
Later editions of her books, which were published by [[Moody Press]], included a disclaimer that said names, dates, and places had been changed.<ref name=Today /> In 1979, Moody Press took the books out of print due to concerns that the books were not presented as fiction.<ref name=Today /> Stafford said the problem arose due to "an unfortunate misunderstanding" between herself and Moody Press, connected to changes in staff and policies at Moody.<ref name=Today /> She maintained that ''Crying Wind'' "is still based on my life", and that her mother was indeed raised on a Kickapoo reservation.<ref name=Today /> Her next publisher, [[Harvest House]], stated that it is honest to call ''Crying Wind'' a "[[biographical novel]]."<ref name=Today />
Her book ''Crying Wind'' sold over 80,000 copies, and has been translated into over a dozen foreign languages.<ref name=Today /><ref name=Dictionary />''Indian Life'' has published two of her other books, ''When the Stars Danced'' and ''Thunder in Our Hearts Lightning in Our Veins'' under their imprint, Sequoyah Editions.<ref>Uttley, Jim. [http://www.assistnews.net/strategic/s0111074.htm "Native American World Indian Life Books Publishes Three New Titles"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929225719/http://www.assistnews.net/strategic/s0111074.htm |date=2011-09-29 }}, ASSIST News Service (November 23, 2010).</ref><ref>Uttley, Jim. [http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2009/s09100155.htm "NATIVE AMERICAN WORLD: Intertribal Christian Communications celebrates 30th anniversary"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416183424/http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2009/s09100155.htm |date=2014-04-16 }}, ASSIST News Service (October 26, 2009).</ref>
==List of her books== *{{Citation |last=Wind |first=Crying |year=1977 |title=Crying Wind |publisher=Moody Press |isbn=978-0-8024-1676-6}} *{{Citation |last=Wind |first=Crying |year=1980 |title=My Searching Heart: A Biographical Novel |publisher=Harvest House |isbn=978-0-89081-262-4}} *{{Citation |last=Wind |first=Crying |year=2001 |title=When the Stars Danced |publisher=Sequoyah Editions |oclc=49222023|isbn=978-0-920379-19-6}} *{{Citation |last=Stafford |first=Linda |year=2007 |title=Thunder in Our Hearts; Lightning in Our Veins |publisher=Intertribal |isbn=978-0-920379-33-2}}
